Analysis of Earnings Per Share(EPS) on Stock Price¶

by Anthony Kim

Earnings Per Share is one of the readily calculated metrics/ratio that is widely used amongst ranges from retailer investors to professional fund managers. Throughout this data science pipeline, we will discuss, observe, and even try to predict the effects of earnings per share on company's stock prices(if we determine to find linear relationship between percentage change of EPS and stock prices).

There are mainly two things that a public company can do with its net profit. They can either retain them and invest into researching or other areas of making the company more valuable, or they can pay dividends to shareholders(stockholders)

If you are not exposed nor particularly familar with the term "earnings per share", it is simply the net income of the company divided by outstanding common shares outstanding during year. For others who may have more understandings about the different financial ratios, please note that earning per share throughout this data science pipeline refers to the basic earning per share metric and NOT the dilutive earning per share (where causing reduction in the value of shareholding due to the issue of additional shares in a company without an increase in asset is considered).

There is not one and clear answer to what is considered as a good EPS, but we will account for the percentage changes of the EPS and its stock prices throughout years in which the calculation intervals are in respect to annual (10-K) reports of the considered public company.

EPS of the companies that have went through the initial public offering (IPO), are available in the Consolidated Statements of Operations (income statement) in the its annual 10-K report/filing made readily accessible in the Securities and Exchange Commision Website. If you are unfamilar with the term EPS, the most important to note is that EPS intends to measure a company's profitability per share. For example, if you want to invest in some company(meaning you desire to be shareholder of some company), it may serve you well to know how much profit the company has made for per share.

We will take a look at percentage change for this tool/metric, EPS, and perform hypothesis testing, and perhaps seek for opportunity in predicting percentage change for the particular stock in which the EPS pertains to (If there exists significant signs of linear relationship between yearly EPS percentage change and yearly stock price percentage change).

Important note about missing data in stock prices are discussed and taken care of towards the bottom.

Additional insights and information: The Global Industry Classification Standard (aka.GICS) is the primary financial industry standard for defining sector classification. The 11 GICS sector that is commonly used includes:

  • Energy
  • Materials
  • Industrials
  • Consumer Discretionary
  • Consumer Staples
  • Health Care
  • Financials
  • Information Technology
  • Telecommunication Services
  • Utilities
  • Real Estate

We are going to experiment on 5 popular Tech public company listed, in regards to how its financial health (determined/considered/affected by particular values from the balance sheet, income statement and cash flow statement) stands in regards to the its stock price. In this pipeline, we use EPS to measure how profitable company is per one share.

# Function that takes in sector_list and plots EPS vs. year for every 
# company in the given list 

def graph_eps_year(sector_list):
    # first set up the fig,ax subplot
    print(type(sector_list))
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,10))
    
    # iterate through each of the stocks inside the sector and graph the years on x axis and eps on y axis
    for stock in sector_list:
        stock_yrs = stock.columns[:-1]
        stock_eps = stock.loc['eps']
        # turn into list and sort the years into ascending order.
        # also remember to reverse the values for eps list since we are basically reversing the years
        stock_yrs = list(stock_yrs)
        stock_eps = list(stock_eps[:-1].values)
        stock_yrs.reverse()
        stock_eps.reverse()
        ticker_name = stock.at['eps', 'Ticker']
#         print("we are working on: ", ticker_name)
#         print(stock_yrs)
#         print(stock_eps)
        ax.plot(stock_yrs, stock_eps, label=ticker_name)
    ax.set_title("EPS vs. year")
    ax.set_xlabel("Year")
    ax.set_ylabel("Earnings Per Share (EPS)")
    ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor = (1,1))

def graph_eps_year_ind(sector_list):
    # first set up the fig,ax subplot
    # and also get the length of the sector_list
    # since we also want to print out the plot in each subplot
    sector_length = len(sector_list)
    fig2, ax2 = plt.subplots(sector_length, figsize=(15,10))
    # initialize counter here
    counter = 0
    
    # iterate through each of the stocks inside the sector and graph the years on x axis and eps on y axis
    for stock in sector_list:
        stock_yrs = stock.columns[:-1]
        stock_eps = stock.loc['eps']
        # turn into list and sort the years into ascending order.
        # also remember to reverse the values for eps list since we are basically reversing the years
        stock_yrs = list(stock_yrs)
        stock_eps = list(stock_eps[:-1].values)
        stock_yrs.reverse()
        stock_eps.reverse()
        ticker_name = stock.at['eps', 'Ticker']
#         print("we are working on: ", ticker_name)
#         print(stock_yrs)
#         print(stock_eps)
        ax2[counter].plot(stock_yrs, stock_eps)
        ax2[counter].set_title("EPS vs. year for " + ticker_name)
        ax2[counter].set_xlabel("Year")
        ax2[counter].set_ylabel("Earnings Per Share (EPS)")
        counter += 1
    fig2.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# define function eps percentage change year function. 

def graph_epsPCT_year(sector_list: List[str]):
    # first set up the fig,ax subplot
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,10))
    
    # iterate through each of the stocks inside the sector and graph the years on x axis and eps on y axis
    for stock in sector_list:
        stock_yrs = stock.columns[:-1]
        stock_eps = stock.loc['eps']
        # turn into list and sort the years into ascending order.
        # also remember to reverse the values for eps list since we are basically reversing the years
        stock_yrs = list(stock_yrs)
        stock_eps = list(stock_eps[:-1].values)
        stock_yrs.reverse()
        stock_eps.reverse()
        # cut out anything that isnt in range 2000-2020
        counter_valid_year = 0
        for year in stock_yrs:
            if (int(year) < 2000):
                counter_valid_year += 1
        stock_yrs = stock_yrs[counter_valid_year:]
        stock_eps = stock_eps[counter_valid_year:]
        # now we should calculate the percentage change. Remeber to input 0 for the very first index 
        # since the percentage change is zero for first year compared to itself(first year)
        stock_eps_pct = [((stock_eps[i]-stock_eps[i-1])/stock_eps[i-1]) for i in range(1, len(stock_eps))]
        stock_eps_pct.insert(0,0)
        ticker_name = stock.at['eps', 'Ticker']
#         print("we are working on: ", ticker_name)
#         print(len(stock_yrs))
#         print(len(stock_eps_pct))
#         print(stock_yrs)
#         print(stock_eps)
#         print(stock_eps_pct)
        ax.plot(stock_yrs, stock_eps_pct, label=ticker_name)
    ax.set_title("EPS Percentage change in respect to year")
    ax.set_xlabel("Year")
    ax.set_ylabel("EPS Percentage Change")
    ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor = (1,1))

def graph_D2D_PCT_year(sector_tickers: List[str]):
    # subplot instantiation
    nfigure, naxes = plt.subplots(len(sector_tickers), figsize=(15,10))
    
    length_tickers = len(sector_tickers)
    counter = 0
    
    for ticker in sector_tickers:
        data = pdr.get_data_yahoo(ticker, start="2000-01-01", end="2020-01-01", interval='d')
        data.tail()
    
    # we need to iterate through the data df and put into lists which the dates are 01-01. 
    # This will make lot easier to calculate percentage changes from year to year since we 
    # have calculated eps percentage yearly.
        years_list = []
        close_price_list = []

        for index, row in data.iterrows():
            year = index.strftime("%y")
            month = index.strftime("%m")
            day = index.strftime("%d")
    
            years_list.append(index)
            close_price_list.append(data.at[index,'Close'])

        # check if same length
#         print(len(years_list))
#         print(len(close_price_list))
        # calculate percentage change

        price_pct = [((close_price_list[i]-close_price_list[i-1])/close_price_list[i-1]) for i in range(1, len(close_price_list))]
        price_pct.insert(0,0)

        naxes[counter].set_title("Day to Day pct of stock prices of " + ticker)
        naxes[counter].set_xlabel("Year")
        naxes[counter].set_ylabel("price d-d pct")
        naxes[counter].plot(years_list, price_pct, label=ticker)
        counter += 1
    nfigure.tight_layout()

Above graph of daily percentage of change of the stock price looks very noisy. Large part of it is because majority of the market is filled with high frequency and algorithmic tradings, so these intraday noises are inevitable. We want the change in yearly basis, not daily.

It makes plausible sense that we calculate percentage changes of the stock with the account to yearly basis since our EPS and EPS percentage change calculation was also through yearly basis. This is due to the fundamental nature of the metric we are using (EPS) since companies gives financial reports quarterly (through document 10-Q) or through annual/yearly (through document 10-K) and because we have decided earlier that we wanted to investigate in terms of year, specifically for the time period of 2000 ~ 2020.

Important information to know before looking at graph_pricePCT_year: The reason why we are getting the stock prices dataframe in the interval of 'm'=month (options were either by day or by month) is because we want to calculate the percentage change of the stock prices in terms of years. This is because for percentage change for stocks from day to day is not meaningful in terms of what we are trying to do. Intraday percentage and for percentage changes of (e.g. today's closing price to yesterday's) stocks will look often strange because there are instituinal traders and algorithms that are performing high frequency trading and often these may look (and often considered) like noise to an investor focused on year-year basis.

# function that plots each of the ticker/company's stock prices during 
# the period/intervals of 2000-01-01 ~ 2020-01-01 if available
def graph_pricePCT_year(sector_tickers: List[str]):
    # classic subplot instantiation
    figure, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,10))
    axes.set_title("Yearly Percentage Change of Stock Prices vs. Time")
    axes.set_xlabel("Year")
    axes.set_ylabel("Stock Price Percentage Change")
    
    
    for ticker in sector_tickers:
        data = pdr.get_data_yahoo(ticker, start="2000-12-27", end="2020-12-27", interval='m')
        data.tail()
        
    # we need to iterate through the data df and put into lists which the dates are 01-01. 
    # This will make lot easier to calculate percentage changes from year to year since we 
    # have calculated eps percentage yearly.
        years_list = []
        close_price_list = []

        for index, row in data.iterrows():
            year = index.strftime("%y")
            month = index.strftime("%m")
            day = index.strftime("%d")
            if (month == '12' and day == '01'):
                years_list.append(index)
                close_price_list.append(data.at[index,'Close'])
#                 print(year)

        # calculate percentage change

        price_pct = [((close_price_list[i]-close_price_list[i-1])/close_price_list[i-1]) for i in range(1, len(close_price_list))]
        price_pct.insert(0,0)

        axes.plot(years_list, price_pct, label=ticker)
    axes.legend(bbox_to_anchor = (1,1))

# start making the essential dataframe for both the EPS yearly percentage change and 
# yearly stock price changes to go in 
def create_essential_df(sector_list):
    data_list_dicts = []
    # iterate through each of the stocks inside the sector and graph the years on x axis and eps on y axis
    for stock in sector_list:
        
        stock_yrs = stock.columns[:-1]
        stock_eps = stock.loc['eps']
        # turn into list and sort the years into ascending order.
        # also remember to reverse the values for eps list since we are basically reversing the years
        stock_yrs = list(stock_yrs)
        stock_eps = list(stock_eps[:-1].values)
        stock_yrs.reverse()
        stock_eps.reverse()
        # cut out anything that isnt in range 2000-2020
        counter_valid_year = 0
        for year in stock_yrs:
            if (int(year) < 2000):
                counter_valid_year += 1
        stock_yrs = stock_yrs[counter_valid_year:]
        stock_eps = stock_eps[counter_valid_year:]
        # now we should calculate the percentage change. Remeber to input 0 for the very first index 
        # since the percentage change is zero for first year compared to itself(first year)
        stock_eps_pct = [((stock_eps[i]-stock_eps[i-1])/stock_eps[i-1]) for i in range(1, len(stock_eps))]
        stock_eps_pct.insert(0,0)
        ticker_name = stock.at['eps', 'Ticker']
#         print("we are working on: ", ticker_name)
#         print(len(stock_yrs))
#         print(len(stock_eps_pct))
                
        index_counter = 0
        for i in range(0,len(stock_yrs)):
            data_list_dicts.append({'Ticker': ticker_name, 
                                    'Year': stock_yrs[index_counter],
                                     'EPS yearly PCT': stock_eps_pct[index_counter]})
            index_counter += 1

    essential_df=pd.DataFrame(data_list_dicts)
    return essential_df

# function that returns dictionary of year to EPS yearly PCT. 
def get_ticker_to_dict(stock_Ticker):
    data = pdr.get_data_yahoo(stock_Ticker, start="2000-12-01", end="2020-12-01", interval='m')
    data.tail()
        
    years_list = []
    close_price_list = []

    for index, row in data.iterrows():
        year = index.strftime("%y")
        month = index.strftime("%m")
        day = index.strftime("%d")
        if (month == '12' and day == '01'):
            years_list.append('20'+year)
            close_price_list.append(data.at[index,'Close'])

    # calculate percentage change
    price_pct = [((close_price_list[i]-close_price_list[i-1])/close_price_list[i-1]) for i in range(1, len(close_price_list))]
    price_pct.insert(0,0)
    result = dict(zip(years_list, price_pct))
    return result

Missing Data¶

Important information about MISSING DATA: About the possibilities/cases on missing data:

  1. Company may have not went public for given time.
  2. The nature of the annual calculation of percentage change in stock prices involves choosing specific date that can be compared from year to year basis. *If this date happens to be saturday/sunday, the market is obviously closed. This is a substantial problem since if for example we have stock closing price on year1, and year2, and year3, and year2 closing price is missing because the chosen date may be saturday or sunday (since any date specific date is not guarenteed to be the same day across all years), this will significantly effect the calculation of percentage change. SOLUTION: I have found a way around it by finding the next consecutive day if the date is missing. Using parameter interval ='m' instead of interval='d' when we are fetching stock prices data from yahoo finance allows us to get the closing price of the next weekday consecutive day if the specific date chosen ends up being saturday,sunday. It makes sense since it will prevent the big problem of having no data and affecting the yearly stock price percentage change, and also because blue chips stocks with significant amount of market capitalizations do not usually tend to have price swings that are very signifcant intraday and between say "2 days"

Hypothesis Testing¶

Before we go further into plotting and hypothesis testing, I am going to define the null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis here:

  • Null hypothesis: There is no linear correlationship between EPS yearly PCT and StockPrice yearly PCT.
  • Alternative hypothesis: There is linear correlationship between EPS yearly PCT and StockPrice yearly PCT.
  • Significance Level (Alpha): $\alpha$ = 0.05
In [125]:
# scattor plot EPS yearly PCT on x-axis and StockPrice yearly PCT on y-axis
fig5, ax5 = plt.subplots()
essential_df['EPS yearly PCT']
ax5.scatter(essential_df['EPS yearly PCT'], essential_df['StockPrice yearly PCT'])

# we can also try fitting the linear regression model
# this will help in spotting linear relationship 
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
ind = [[i] for i in essential_df['EPS yearly PCT'].values]
dep = [[j] for j in essential_df['StockPrice yearly PCT'].values]
reg = LinearRegression().fit(ind, dep)
ax5.plot(essential_df['EPS yearly PCT'], reg.predict(ind))
ax5.set_title("StockPrice yearly PCT vs. EPS yearly PCT")
ax5.set_xlabel("EPS yearly PCT")
ax5.set_ylabel("StockPrice yearly PCT")
Out[125]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'StockPrice yearly PCT')
In [126]:
import scipy.stats
scipy.stats.pearsonr(essential_df['EPS yearly PCT'], essential_df['StockPrice yearly PCT'])
Out[126]:
(0.05844764220531987, 0.5907577519369059)

As you can see in the scatter plot of StockPrice yearly PCT vs. EPS yearly PCT, there isn't seem to be linear correlation between the StockPrice yearly PCT and EPS yearly PCT. Also observing the pearson's correlation coefficient (of 0.05844764220531987) and the p-value (0.5907577519369059), we fail to reject the null hypothesis of there is no linear relationship between EPS yearly PCT and StockPrice yearly PCT. Also note that the pearson's correlation coefficient seems very low/unlikely implying absence of linear relationship between the two datasets of essential_df['EPS yearly PCT'] and essential_df['StockPrice yearly PCT']

However, there is still possibility of linear relationship between StockPrice yearly PCT and EPS yearly PCT, which can be visualized/explored through plotting this graph of StockPrice yearly PCT and EPS yearly PCT SEPARATELY for each stock(ticker).

In [127]:
# Plot individually.

Conclusion¶

Throughout this data science pipepline, I have walked through exploring and analyzing the potential linear relationship between Earnings Per Share on specifically chosen tech stock and its stock prices. Exploratory analysis and the hypothesis testing may have not provided results that will satisfy investors (or I should say speculators believing there is a magical simple indicator) who are willing to throw money into the stock market, thinking one ratio will be "sufficient" or "good enough".

The truth is, there are many other factors, not only other fundamental analysis metrics and ratios, but also advanced mathematical models and high frequency algorithmic trading and speculation that is dominating the market today. I hope that this data science pipeline clearly showed you that one indepedent variable is not sufficient enough nor a guarentee to predict the stock prices today.
